    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Tellina alfredensis</i><strong> </strong>and hence also given the common name ‘Port Alfred tellin’. That no longer seems appropriate though, so we have also changed the common name to a more descriptive one based on the species name. Also previously named <i>Tellina palliderosea.</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_895",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Large for a tellin and with smooth (other than faint concentric growth lines), laterally-compressed shells that are distinctively extended and curved to the right at the posterior end.&nbsp; Colour a striking pale pink, often with paler and darker growth bands; colouration more vivid on inner surface of shells.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_896",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Relatively large, at up to 85 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_897",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> &nbsp;False Bay to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_898",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Burrows in sediments from low water to about 3 m depth. Lies horizontally with the left valve downwards and the elongate inhalant siphon projecting above the sediment surface and held horizontally to vacuum–up fine particulate material lying on, or close to, the sediment surface. Shells commonly washed-up after storms.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_899",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves feeds by pumping water in via an inhalant siphon, filtering out fine particles though the enlarged gills and then ejecting the filtered water through an exhalent siphon. &nbsp;Because of their feeding habits, tellins tend to suck in large amounts of sand along with their food material and thus have large labial palps, which are used to sort the incoming particle stream.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_900",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves is a broadcast spawner. Details of reproductive cycle of this species in South Africa have not been investigated.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_901",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>One of the best know local bivalves and unlikely to be confused with other regional species due to the large size and striking colour.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_902",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 154).<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 181).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_903",
